<p>A dehydrogenation enthalpy of about 40 kJ/mol is required in order to meet the dehydrogenation temperature compatible with PEMFCs [
 <xref rid="B328-materials-12-02724" ref-type="bibr">328</xref>]. This enthalpy value roughly means an equilibrium pressure of 1 bar at room temperature. The equilibrium pressure is a function of the temperature, the dehydrogenation enthalpy, and entropy. It is described by the Van’t Hoff equation [
 <xref rid="B328-materials-12-02724" ref-type="bibr">328</xref>]: 
 <disp-formula id="FD14-materials-12-02724">
  <label>(97)</label>
  <math id="mm23">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>ln</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mfrac>
        <mrow>
         <msub>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mrow>
           <mi>e</mi>
           <mi>q</mi>
          </mrow>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
         <msubsup>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mrow>
           <mi>e</mi>
           <mi>q</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mn>0</mn>
         </msubsup>
        </mrow>
       </mfrac>
      </mrow>
      <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mo>Δ</mo>
       <mi>H</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mi>R</mi>
     </mfrac>
     <mo>×</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mi>T</mi>
     </mfrac>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mo>Δ</mo>
       <mi>S</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mi>R</mi>
     </mfrac>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
